 to fight the disease. The current NACI recommended immunization schedule is specifically designed to protect children when they are most at risk.</p><h2>How vaccine ingredients have changed:</h2><p>Despite the increase in the total number of vaccines given, children are exposed to fewer foreign proteins (antigens) in vaccines today than in the past. Until 1972, children received about 200 proteins from just the smallpox vaccine. Today, with advances in protein chemistry, the 14 routinely recommended vaccines contain fewer than 150 proteins in total. In other words, all of the vaccines given to children today have fewer overall antigens than the smallpox vaccine alone.</p><h2>Babies are well equipped to fight off germs in the environment:</h2><p>Infants have an enormous capacity to respond safely and effectively to multiple vaccines. From the moment they are born, infants are exposed to trillions of germs in the environment and their immune systems are well equipped to handle the immune response produced by the vaccine. The immunological challenge from vaccines is very small compared to what babies’ immune systems deal with every day. In other words, babies’ immune systems are constantly fighting off germs from others and their environments every day.</p><h2>Safety is the #1 consideration:</h2><p>Before vaccines are approved for use, their safety is studied extensively. They are tested alone and in combination with the existing vaccines to determine whether they affect the safety of the other vaccines. These multiple vaccine studies are always done before a new vaccine is added to the vaccination schedule.</p><h2>What the studies say:</h2><p>A study published in the Journal of Pediatrics titled 'On-time Vaccine Receipt in the First Year Does Not Adversely Affect Neuropsychological Outcomes” compared children who had received all their vaccines on time during the first year of life with children who did not, looking for differences in neuropsychological (this means the brain and behavior connections) outcomes at 7 to 10 years of age. The study found that timely vaccination during infancy did not cause neuropsychological outcomes in children 7 to 10 years of age and later.</p><p>There is no evidence that timely receipt of currently recommended vaccines overloads or weakens the child’s immune system. Vaccine decline or delay, on the other hand, may leave a child at risk for vaccine-preventable diseases, such as whooping cough and pneumococcal disease.</p><h2>References:</h2><ul><li><a href='http://www.cdc.gov/vaccines/vac-gen/whatifstop.htm'>http://www.cdc.gov/vaccines/vac-gen/whatifstop.htm</a></li><li>Offit PA, Quarles J, Gerber MA, Hackett CJ, Marcuse EK, Kollman TR, Gellin BG, Landry S. Addressing parents’ concerns: do multiple vaccines overwhelm or weaken the infant’s immune system? Pediatrics. 2002 Jan;109(1):124-9. Review</li><li>Gregson AL, Edelman R. Does antigenic overload exist? The role of multiple immunizations in infants. Immunol Allergy Clin North Am. 2003 Nov;23(4):649-64. Review</li><li>Wharton M. Vaccine safety: current systems and recent findings. Curr Opin Pediatr. 2010 Feb;22(1):88-93. Review</li><li>Smith MJ, Woods CR. On-time vaccine receipt in the first year does not adversely affect neuropsychological outcomes. Pediatrics. 2010 Jun;125(6):1134-41.</li><li>PHAC. Frequently asked questions: what would happen if we stopped immunizing? web page. Accessed at <a href='http://www.phac-aspc.gc.ca/im/vs-sv/vs-faq06-eng.php'>http://www.phac-aspc.gc.ca/im/vs-sv/vs-faq06-eng.php</a> on 30 Sept 2015.</li><li>Immunization Canada. Will multiple injections overwhelm the immune system? Web page. Accessed at <a href='http://immunize.ca/en/publications-resources/questions/multiple.aspx'>http://immunize.ca/en/publications-resources/questions/multiple.aspx</a> on 30 Sept 2015.</p>"
